As Ashley wrote to Dr. Math
On 08/16/2004 at 19:04:11 (Eastern Time),
>[Question]
>How can I arrange the digits 1,2,3,4,5,6,7 into an addition problem 
>so that they equal 100?
>
>[Difficulty]
>Getting them grouped so that they equal 100.
>
>[Thoughts]
>7+6=13+5=18+4=22=+3=25+2=27+1=28         Can not use numbers more 
>than once.

That's what you get if you just make each digit a separate number, so 
that all the digits are in the ones (units) place. To get a bigger 
number, you'll need to move some of the digits to the tens place. 
Which ones should they be? There are several ways you could do this.

